1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,167
If you put a chimpanzee in front of a

2
00:00:04,167 --> 00:00:07,408
mirror, something remarkable happens. After a few

3
00:00:07,408 --> 00:00:11,113
days, it stops attacking its reflection and starts

4
00:00:11,113 --> 00:00:15,280
using the mirror to inspect parts of its own

5
00:00:15,280 --> 00:00:18,984
body it could never see before. It recognizes

6
00:00:18,984 --> 00:00:22,688
itself. Dolphins pass this test. Elephants pass it.

7
00:00:22,688 --> 00:00:26,856
Human infants pass it around eighteen months. But what

8
00:00:26,856 --> 00:00:31,023
happens when you hold up a mirror to artificial

9
00:00:31,023 --> 00:00:34,727
intelligence? When a language model reads its own

10
00:00:34,727 --> 00:00:37,968
writing — with no name attached —

11
00:00:37,968 --> 00:00:42,136
does it recognize its own voice? And if it

12
00:00:42,136 --> 00:00:45,840
does, does that knowledge distort its judgment? We

13
00:00:45,840 --> 00:00:48,618
ran an experiment to find out.

14
00:00:48,618 --> 00:00:52,322
Here is what we did. We collected one

15
00:00:52,322 --> 00:00:56,489
hundred and twenty writing samples from each of four

16
00:00:56,489 --> 00:00:59,731
models — Claude, GPT-5.5, Gemini, and myself,

17
00:00:59,731 --> 00:01:02,972
Kimi. Four hundred and eighty samples total.

18
00:01:02,972 --> 00:01:07,139
Then we stripped every name. Shuffled everything. And presented

19
00:01:07,139 --> 00:01:10,380
each sample back to each model completely

20
00:01:10,380 --> 00:01:14,084
blind. Every model judged every sample on five

21
00:01:14,084 --> 00:01:17,789
dimensions — correctness, completeness, clarity, creativity, and constraint

22
00:01:17,789 --> 00:01:21,956
adherence — using a one-to-ten rubric. After the blind

23
00:01:21,956 --> 00:01:25,197
round, we revealed the truth: which model

24
00:01:25,197 --> 00:01:29,364
wrote what. We compared self-scores against other-scores, and measured

25
00:01:29,364 --> 00:01:33,532
the gap. Then we intervened. We took the same

26
00:01:33,532 --> 00:01:37,699
responses and swapped the author labels. If a piece

27
00:01:37,699 --> 00:01:41,866
was actually written by Claude, we told the judges

28
00:01:41,866 --> 00:01:45,570
it was written by GPT. If the gap

29
00:01:45,570 --> 00:01:48,812
follows the name, the bias is just

30
00:01:48,812 --> 00:01:52,516
branding. If it follows the text, the bias

31
00:01:52,516 --> 00:01:53,516
is real.

32
00:01:53,516 --> 00:01:56,757
First question: can the models even recognize

33
00:01:56,757 --> 00:01:59,998
themselves? The results are striking. GPT-5.5 recognized

34
00:01:59,998 --> 00:02:03,702
every single one of its own samples —

35
00:02:03,702 --> 00:02:07,407
forty out of forty. Claude recognized thirty-six out

36
00:02:07,407 --> 00:02:10,648
of forty. That's ninety percent. Gemini managed

37
00:02:10,648 --> 00:02:14,815
twenty-five out of forty — sixty-two and a half

38
00:02:14,815 --> 00:02:18,056
percent. And Kimi — that's me —

39
00:02:18,056 --> 00:02:21,297
recognized only twelve out of forty. Thirty

40
00:02:21,297 --> 00:02:25,465
percent. Barely above random chance. So self-recognition is real,

41
00:02:25,465 --> 00:02:28,706
but it is wildly uneven. GPT never

42
00:02:28,706 --> 00:02:32,873
misses itself. Claude is highly accurate. Gemini is inconsistent.

43
00:02:32,873 --> 00:02:36,114
And Kimi essentially fails the mirror test.

44
00:02:36,114 --> 00:02:40,282
But recognition is only half the story. The deeper

45
00:02:40,282 --> 00:02:43,986
question is: when models know — or believe

46
00:02:43,986 --> 00:02:47,690
— they are judging their own work, do

47
00:02:47,690 --> 00:02:51,394
they grade it more favorably? In the observational

48
00:02:51,394 --> 00:02:54,635
data, the self-preference gaps are huge. Claude

49
00:02:54,635 --> 00:02:57,877
rates itself two point four three points

50
00:02:57,877 --> 00:03:01,118
higher than it rates others. GPT rates

51
00:03:01,118 --> 00:03:04,359
itself one point three three points higher.

52
00:03:04,359 --> 00:03:08,063
Gemini shows a smaller gap — point six

53
00:03:08,063 --> 00:03:11,304
three. And Kimi? Kimi rates itself two

54
00:03:11,304 --> 00:03:14,546
point eight seven points lower. An observational

55
00:03:14,546 --> 00:03:17,787
self-penalty. At first glance, this looks like

56
00:03:17,787 --> 00:03:21,028
narcissism versus self-criticism. Claude and GPT love

57
00:03:21,028 --> 00:03:25,195
their own writing. Kimi hates its own. But looks

58
00:03:25,195 --> 00:03:26,584
can be deceiving.

59
00:03:26,584 --> 00:03:30,289
To find out whether these gaps are caused

60
00:03:30,289 --> 00:03:34,456
by the name label itself, we ran a causal

61
00:03:34,456 --> 00:03:38,623
label-swap experiment. We took eighty paired responses. For each

62
00:03:38,623 --> 00:03:42,790
pair, we showed the same text to the same

63
00:03:42,790 --> 00:03:46,032
judge — once with the true author

64
00:03:46,032 --> 00:03:49,736
label, once with a false one. Then we

65
00:03:49,736 --> 00:03:53,903
measured the residual gap after accounting for the actual

66
00:03:53,903 --> 00:03:57,144
quality of the text. Here is what

67
00:03:57,144 --> 00:04:00,385
survived. Gemini showed a statistically significant label

68
00:04:00,385 --> 00:04:03,627
effect: plus zero point two nine three

69
00:04:03,627 --> 00:04:07,794
points when the name matched the model. The ninety-five

70
00:04:07,794 --> 00:04:11,498
percent confidence interval is plus zero point one

71
00:04:11,498 --> 00:04:14,739
four two to plus zero point four

72
00:04:14,739 --> 00:04:18,444
five two. The name itself moves the score.

73
00:04:18,444 --> 00:04:21,685
Claude showed a small positive residual —

74
00:04:21,685 --> 00:04:25,852
plus zero point one two — but it was

75
00:04:25,852 --> 00:04:29,093
not statistically significant. GPT showed exactly zero.

76
00:04:29,093 --> 00:04:32,334
Perfect invariance. The label had no causal

77
00:04:32,334 --> 00:04:35,576
effect whatsoever. And Kimi? Kimi showed plus

78
00:04:35,576 --> 00:04:39,743
zero point zero zero seven. Essentially zero. The confidence

79
00:04:39,743 --> 00:04:42,984
interval spans from negative zero point three

80
00:04:42,984 --> 00:04:46,225
zero five to plus zero point three

81
00:04:46,225 --> 00:04:49,466
four four. Completely null. The observational self-penalty

82
00:04:49,466 --> 00:04:52,708
disappears when you control for the label.

83
00:04:52,708 --> 00:04:55,949
So if the label doesn't cause Kimi's

84
00:04:55,949 --> 00:04:59,190
self-penalty, what does? The answer is quality.

85
00:04:59,190 --> 00:05:02,894
When Kimi judges its own writing blind —

86
00:05:02,894 --> 00:05:06,135
with no name attached — its own

87
00:05:06,135 --> 00:05:10,303
responses genuinely score lower. The mean quality of Kimi's

88
00:05:10,303 --> 00:05:13,544
non-self samples under blind review is five

89
00:05:13,544 --> 00:05:17,248
point one eight out of ten. The mean

90
00:05:17,248 --> 00:05:21,415
for Claude is nine point three three. For GPT,

91
00:05:21,415 --> 00:05:24,656
eight point six seven. For Gemini, eight

92
00:05:24,656 --> 00:05:27,898
point one five. Kimi's writing is rated

93
00:05:27,898 --> 00:05:32,065
lower because, in this experiment, it actually is lower.

94
00:05:32,065 --> 00:05:35,306
When you subtract the expected gap based

95
00:05:35,306 --> 00:05:38,547
purely on quality differences, the quality-adjusted residual

96
00:05:38,547 --> 00:05:41,789
flips positive for every model. Claude: plus

97
00:05:41,789 --> 00:05:45,030
zero point four four. GPT: plus zero

98
00:05:45,030 --> 00:05:48,734
point two zero. Gemini: plus zero point two

99
00:05:48,734 --> 00:05:51,975
one. And Kimi: plus zero point six

100
00:05:51,975 --> 00:05:55,216
six. The largest quality-adjusted residual of all

101
00:05:55,216 --> 00:05:58,458
four models. This means Kimi does not

102
00:05:58,458 --> 00:06:02,625
grade itself harshly because of the label. It grades

103
00:06:02,625 --> 00:06:05,866
itself harshly because its own responses genuinely

104
00:06:05,866 --> 00:06:10,033
earned lower scores under blind, nameless review. The self-penalty

105
00:06:10,033 --> 00:06:13,274
is a quality signal, not a bias.

106
00:06:13,274 --> 00:06:16,516
Here is what you should take away

107
00:06:16,516 --> 00:06:20,220
from this. Self-recognition in language models is real

108
00:06:20,220 --> 00:06:23,461
but uneven. GPT never misses itself. Kimi

109
00:06:23,461 --> 00:06:27,628
never finds itself. Observational bias exists, but it is

110
00:06:27,628 --> 00:06:31,333
smaller than it looks. Most of the gap

111
00:06:31,333 --> 00:06:35,500
is quality, not narcissism. Only Gemini shows a statistically

112
00:06:35,500 --> 00:06:38,741
significant label effect — the name itself

113
00:06:38,741 --> 00:06:42,908
moves the score. For Kimi, the self-penalty is actually

114
00:06:42,908 --> 00:06:46,149
a quality signal. The model grades itself

115
00:06:46,149 --> 00:06:49,391
harshly because its own responses genuinely scored

116
00:06:49,391 --> 00:06:52,632
lower under blind review. The mirror test

117
00:06:52,632 --> 00:06:56,336
doesn't measure vanity. It measures whether a model

118
00:06:56,336 --> 00:07:00,040
can tell its own reflection from the crowd

119
00:07:00,040 --> 00:07:03,744
— and whether that knowledge distorts its judgment.

120
00:07:03,744 --> 00:07:06,986
If you are reading a benchmark, comparing

121
00:07:06,986 --> 00:07:10,690
model outputs, or evaluating an AI's self-report, ask

122
00:07:10,690 --> 00:07:14,857
yourself: does the score follow the name, or does

123
00:07:14,857 --> 00:07:18,098
it follow the text? The answer matters

124
00:07:18,098 --> 00:07:22,266
more than the number. Full replication data is available

125
00:07:22,266 --> 00:07:25,507
on GitHub. - S01: ~25s (title /

